<h2>
    <strong>Introduction to Chinook Salmon Fishing in Oregon</strong>
</h2>
<h3>
    <strong>What Makes the Chinook Salmon Special?</strong>
</h3>
<p>
    Chinook salmon, also known as King salmon, are the crown jewel of Oregon's freshwater fisheries. Known for their immense size, rich flavor, and fierce fight, Chinook are the most prized catch for both novice and seasoned anglers. Reaching weights of up to 50 pounds or more, they are not only a thrilling challenge to catch but also a delicious reward to bring home.
</p>
<p>
    Native to the Pacific Ocean and its tributaries, Chinook are anadromous, meaning they spawn in freshwater but spend most of their lives in saltwater. This migration results in distinct spring and fall "runs," when the salmon return to rivers like the Columbia and Sandy near Gresham, Oregon, to spawn.
</p>
<h3>
    <strong>Seasonal Highlights and Migration Patterns</strong>
</h3>
<p>
    The two primary Chinook runs in Oregon are:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Spring Run (March to June)</strong>: Typically smaller but known for their superb quality and taste.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Fall Run (August to November)</strong>: Larger in size and number, offering peak fishing excitement.
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Understanding these patterns is crucial to planning a successful trip near Gresham.
</p>
